<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-710-13> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "710-13\r\nKiowa doll cradle (pajop, Merrill et.al. 1997:62; paih'dodl, Hail 2002:23); wood, hide, cloth, glass, brass, papier maché; l. 74 cm., w. 24 cm., h. 16.5 cm.; ca. 1875.\r\nThe Kiowas made cradles in three sizes: model cradles for dolls to play with, a small size cradle for newborn babies, and a slightly larger one for older infants. The rawhide bib, protecting the head of the infant, is typical for Kiowa cradles, and is present in this model. This slat-frame (Osage orange [Maclura pomifera] = bois d'arc (yes) or made from cedar?) is partially covered with cloth, and canvas and cloth almost completely replaced hides during the late 19th century. The curvilinear, abstract leaf shape is outlined in undulating vertical rows of white beads sewn in spot-stitch, the resulting panels filled in with red and blue beads in lazy stitch. The designs used were regarded as individual property, but bead workers occasionally allowed others to use their motifs. The emphasis by Kiowa bead workers on originality resulted in a great artistic variety of cradles (Conn 1979:154; Hail 1980:143-146; 2002:26-29; Schneider 1983:239; 1983a; Brasser 1998:54-55; Levy 2001:910; Merrill et.al. 1979:18-19,50,53-4,130-131).\r\n(Hovens 2008-09)\r\n\r\n\r\n362-14; 710-13 Southern Plains cradles.\r\nWhile Barbara Hail of the Haffenreffer Museum of Anthropology in Bristol, Rhode Island, was doing fieldwork on Southern Plains Indian cradles, her Kiowa-Delaware informant Linda Poolaw aptly defined their meaning as \"a house for the beginning of life.\" They were \"gifts of pride and love\" as a descendant of a cradle maker called them.\r\nOriginally cradles consisted of a board slightly longer and wider than the body of the infant, on which the baby was secured by hide bindings, swaddled in skins. Later, wooden sides were added. The lattice or slat-frame cradle appeared after 1830, and became prevalent among the Comanches, Kiowas, Arapahos, Cheyennes, and Lakotas. It consisted of two narrow pointed boards and two shorter cross sections that were made into a sturdy V-shaped frame of which the longs boards pointed outwards at the top. Such construction and the decoration of the frame were usually done by men. Rawhide was used for backing the frame, and as protective strips for head and feet, and a hide cover in which the baby was swaddled was laced onto that construction. Their adoption facilitated transportation of babies on horseback by hanging cradles from pommels. Children usually spent most of their first two years of their lives swaddles and cradled. Swaddling was a widespread practice in Native North America as it was believed that it physically protected infants, quieted them down, strengthened their muscles, and resulted in a strong bond with mothers (Mason 1887:198-203; Orchard 1929:168; Berlandier 1969:87-88; Hail 1980:143-151; 2003:17,23-25,31-34; Schneider 1983a; Hovens and Krosenbrink 1994; cf. Walton et.al. 1985:172-179 for northern Plains cradles). Cradle RMV 362-14 was stolen during an exhibition.\r\n(Hovens, 2008-09)\r\n\r\nINDIAANSE POPPEN\r\n\r\nPLAINS (buckskin dolls)\r\nMaterialen: hout, stof of huid (Lenz 1986:33).\r\nZogenaamde ‘pieces dolls’ waren gemaakt van restjes stof en vrij eenvoudig van vorm. Meestal droegen deze poppen slechts een shawl, en werden zij net als poppen van Europese kinderen vaak aan- en uitgekleed.\r\nMet paarden gemaakt van twijgjes of huid, en miniatuur tipi’s speelden kinderen (bij de meeste groepen deden jongens ook mee) dat zij onderweg waren en een kamp inrichtten. De meisjes leerden zo bijvoorbeeld hoe een tipi op te zetten, een taak die voor vrouwen was weggelegd en waar deze nog steeds trots op zijn. De jongens speelden dat hun poppen gingen jagen of oorlog voeren. De poppen hadden tevens miniatuur cradleboards, en andere gebruiksvoorwerpen om hun wereld compleet te maken. Kinderen spelen nog steeds ‘kampje’, volgens Lenz, omdat het ‘fun’ is (Lenz 1986:34).\r\nTMS: 362-14, 710-13, 3158-14 en 15.\r\n(PH, 2000)" .
